comment.narrative:
Capacity for climate-related analysis and forward planning is  limited at sub-national level with an average CCA capacity score of 1.26 across the 5 functional areas of

- Multi-stakeholder dialogue;

- Situation analysis, vision casting and mandate;

- Policy and strategy formulation;

- Budget, Manage and Implement;

- Monitoring and Evaluation

1. Percentage of national coverage of the weather/climate and hydrological monitoring network at the beginning of the project:
Meteorological stations: 1,000 manual, 70 automatic;
Hydrological stations: 489 manual, 4 with telemetry. 2. Frequency of data transmission and collection: monthly.

1. Increase in 24% national coverage to take steps in achieving NMAs optimal monitoring arrangements as defined in feasibility studies:
Meteorological stations: 1240 manual stations, 110 automatic;
Hydrological stations: 439 manual, 64 with telemetry. 2. Frequency of data transmission and collection: daily.

1. Use of hydro-meteorological and environmental information for making early warnings is currently low for both women and men.
Women: 6 million;
Men: 8 million. 2. Currently no development frameworks incorporate climate change information. 3. Limited number of tailor-made and sector-specific meteorological products. Limited public-private partnerships and pay for services contracts.

1. Percentage increase in the population who has access to improved EWS/CI (50% increase for women and 50% increase for men).
Women: 9 million;
Men: 12 million. 2. At least 2 of the PRSP policy briefs incorporate analyses of risk maps and/or climate change projections influencing long-term planning proposals. 3. Development of at least one tailored climate product and presentation of a market research plan on how to implement mobile phone based agricultural advisories, both supporting targeted weather/climate service delivery.
